[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Your AI coding agent is wasting almost all of its tokens. Every time it explores a code base, it reads file after file after file, and the bill explodes. This is code base memory MCP, an MCP server that indexes your entire'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'repo into a knowledge graph your agent can query in under a millisecond. There\'s one benchmark number in here that honestly sounds made up until you see it. Stick around because I\'ll put that exact number on screen in a minute.'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here\'s the project\'s documentation site open on my phone. The idea is deceptively simple. Instead of letting your AI agent grep around reading raw files, code base memory MCP parses your entire code base ahead of time into a'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'graph of every function, every type, and every call relationship between them. Then, through the model context protocol, your agent asks precise structural questions. Who calls this function? What\'s the overall'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'architecture? What does this change affect? And gets an exact answer instantly without ever opening a file. It\'s the difference between searching a library shelf by shelf and just checking the catalog. So, what is it exactly?'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Code base memory MCP is a code intelligence server built specifically to feed AI agents. It uses tree-sitter to parse 158 different programming languages into an abstract syntax tree,'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then layers on deeper semantic type resolution with a call hybrid LSP for nine of the big ones like Python, TypeScript, Go, and Rust. The result is a persistent knowledge graph stored'

[01:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'locally that answers structural queries in under a millisecond. And the whole engine is written in pure C with zero runtime dependencies, so it ships as one small static binary that just runs anywhere. And the numbers around this'

[01:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'project are genuinely wild. It rocketed to roughly 8,000 GitHub stars in about 4 months. It parses 158 languages straight out of the box. And to prove it actually scales, the author pointed it at the'

[01:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Linux kernel. 28 million lines of code spread across 75,000 files. And the entire thing in about 3 minutes. This is not a weekend toy. It\'s engineered to chew through some of the'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'largest code bases on the planet without breaking a sweat. Here\'s why this matters so much. The old way, the way most AI agents work right now, is to grep and read files one at a time, pulling huge chunks of raw source into the context window just to answer one'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simple question. It\'s slow, it\'s expensive, and it torches your token budget. Codebase memory MCP flips the whole approach. It answers from a pre-built graph, returns only the exact symbols you asked about, runs every'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'query in under a millisecond, and keeps your code entirely on your own machine. It\'s precise where the old way is brute force. And now that number I promised you in the intro, the maintainers ran the exact same five structural questions'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two different ways. Doing it the old way, file-by-file grep exploration, burned about 412,000 tokens. Doing it through codebase memory MCP\'s graph took roughly 3,400.'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Same questions, same answers, a 99.2% reduction. Look at the chart. The old approach barely fits on the screen, and the new one is a tiny sliver next to it. That single comparison is the number'

[03:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that makes this worth installing today. Getting it running is almost too easy. On Mac or Linux, it\'s a single curl one-liner. The installer pulls down the static binary, then auto-detects which AI agents you already have, Claude Code,'

[03:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cursor, Zed, and eight others, and wires up the MCP configuration for each one automatically. You restart your agent, it indexes your repository once, and from that point on, your assistant'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simply has a memory of your codebase. There\'s no API key, no cloud account, and no separate database to baby-sit. And if you\'d rather wire it up by hand, it\'s just a few lines in your MCP config pointing the command at the binary.'

[03:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here\'s the repository itself, again on mobile. It\'s MIT licensed, written entirely in C, and the The tags read like a who\'s who of AI coding tools: Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, Gemini CLI, WinSurf, I Dare.'

[03:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Nearly 8,000 stars and over 600 forks in just a few months tells you how badly developers wanted exactly this. And it isn\'t locked to a single install method, either. Alongside the static binary, it\'s on NPM, PyPI, Homebrew, Scoop,'

[04:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Winget, and more. So, whatever your setup, there\'s a one-line way in. Under the hood, it exposes 14 MCP tools, and they\'re the ones that actually matter for understanding code.'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can search the graph by name pattern, trace a full call chain in either direction, and pull a whole architecture overview, languages, packages, roots, and hotspots in a single call. You can run read-only'

[04:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cypher-style graph queries directly. There\'s a detect changes tool that maps a Git diff to the exact symbols and the risk it touches. And a semantic search powered by a bundled embedding model that needs no API key whatsoever. And it'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'isn\'t only an API. There\'s an optional graph UI. Fire up the local server, and you get a live interactive 3D visualization of your codebase as a constellation of connected nodes running'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'entirely on localhost. You can literally see the clusters, the hotspots, and the dependency chains that your AI agent is querying behind the scenes. For getting your bearings in an unfamiliar codebase, seeing the whole'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape of it laid out like this is genuinely powerful. And it makes the abstract idea of a code knowledge graph suddenly concrete. The maintainers compress the entire value proposition into a single benchmark line, the one on'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'screen right now. Think about what it\'s really saying. When your token bill and your query latency both collapse by two full orders of magnitude at the same time, that is not a minor optimization. That is a'

[05:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fundamentally different way for an AI agent to work with code, and it\'s a big part of why this little server caught on so fast. And remember just how new all of this is. The repository was created in late February 2026.'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In only a few months, it climbed to around 8,000 stars, shipped a steady run of releases, and reached version 0.8.1 in June. A release that rewrote the graph UI\'s web server entirely from'

[05:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scratch to drop the last third-party dependency from the binary. Going from a standing start to a polished security-hardened tool in a single quarter is its own kind of signal about how much demand there was for this. And'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s the kicker. It\'s the work of one developer. Codebase Memory MCP is built by Martin Vogel, who goes by Dias data on GitHub out of Berlin. He shipped a pure C code intelligence engine complete with SLSA level 3 built provenance,'

[06:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sigstore keyless signatures, and clean VirusTotal scans across more than 70 engines. The kind of supply chain rigor that most well-funded startups quietly skip. It\'s a genuine reminder of how much one'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'focused person can still build and ship on their own. If your AI agent keeps rereading your codebase from scratch, give it a memory instead. Codebase Memory MCP is open source and free. Go point it at your own repo. Thanks for'

